O. XXX. QUOMODO REFORMETUR VAS VITREUM FRACTUM.

This invention appears to have been made in the reign os Tiberius Caesar, and to have led to the sable of malleable glast. Pliny, who bas been quoted by St. Isidore, mentions an invention ol a composition, or tempering, which rendered glass tendet, and that Tiberius, fearing this would depreciate the salue oi the precious metals, abolished the worksbop ol the artificer. This story has been wonderfully improved by St. Isidore, who adds a hammer to the tale, and converts the “tendet” or “ tractable gloss ” mentioned by Pliny into one which is “malleable.” Eraclius quotes from St. Isidore, rather than from Pliny, whose version is too plain to admit os the marvellous.

Pliny writes, “ Ferunt, Tiberio principe, excogitatum vitri tem- peramentum, ut flexibile esset: et totam officinam artificis ejus abolitam, ne aeris, argenti, auri, metallis pretia detraherentur: atique fama crebrior diu, quam certior suit.”²
